"Android is exploring more private ways for apps to show you ads"
"The new privacy features in the Privacy Sandbox let apps show you relevant ads, but restrict what those apps can learn about your activities on websites and apps from other developers."
"Turning on the beta allows apps to test these new, more private ways to show you ads. You can turn off the beta at any time in your privacy settings."
"You’re part of Android’s ads privacy beta. The Privacy Sandbox is turned on for your device.\n\nYou can learn more or turn off the beta at any time in your privacy settings."

"The Privacy Sandbox is on for your device, and apps can test these new, more private ways to show you ads. You can turn off the beta at any time in your privacy settings."

"Android’s Privacy Sandbox provides new features that apps can use to show you ads that you might like. These technologies don’t use device identifiers.\n\nAndroid and your apps can estimate the kind of ads that you might be interested in, and save the interests temporarily on your device. This allows apps to show you ads that you might like, without tracking your activity across websites and apps from other developers."

"Android periodically estimates your top interests based on the apps that you use, for example, 'Sports' or 'Travel'.

Later, an app can ask Android to use these interests to show you more relevant ads.

You can see the list of current interests in your privacy settings, and block any that you don’t like."

"Apps can estimate your interests and temporarily save these with Android. For example, an app that you use to buy running shoes might estimate your interest as 'running marathons'.

Later, based on this interest, a different app can show you an ad related to marathons.

In your privacy settings, you can manage the list of apps that have saved interests."
"Ad topics and new controls give you more choice over the ads that you see"

"Android notes topics of interest based on apps that you’ve used recently. Also, apps that you use can determine what you like. Later, apps can ask for this information to show you personalised ads. You can choose which topics and apps are used to show you ads."
"To measure the performance of an ad, limited types of data are shared between apps."
"Apps can ask Android for information to help personalise the ads that you see."

resources.string: "Apps can use the Privacy Sandbox to measure the effectiveness of their ads. To do this, advertisers can temporarily save data with Android about your interactions between their ads and apps. The amount of data that they can save is restricted and will be deleted regularly.\n\nYou can delete this data at any time by turning off the Privacy Sandbox."

"Android periodically estimates your top interests based on the apps that you use. Apps can ask Android to use these interests to show you more relevant ads.\n\nIf you block an interest, it won’t be added to the list again unless you unblock it. You may still see some related ads."
"No topics to show at the moment.\nLearn more about ""ad topics"

This allows apps to show you relevant ads, without tracking your activity across websites and apps from other developers."

"Apps can estimate your interests and temporarily save these with Android. Later, a different app can show you an ad based on these interests.\n\nIf you block an app, it won’t estimate any more interests. It won’t be added to this list of apps again unless you unblock it. "Android’s ads privacy beta provides new features that apps can use to show you ads that you might like. This allows apps to show you relevant ads, without tracking your activity across websites and apps from other developers."
"Apps and advertisers can request information from Android that helps them measure the performance of their ads.\n\nAd measurement data is deleted regularly from your device."

"Android protects your privacy by limiting the information that apps can share with one another. Reports are sent with a delay to protect your identity.

Your browser may have a similar setting. If ads measurement is on for both Android and your browser, a company may be able to measure the effectiveness of an ad between apps that you use and sites that you visit. Your browsing history is kept private on your device.

Learn more about how Android protects your data in our ""privacy policy""."

string.a: "Learn more about how Android helps to protect your privacy"

resources.string:
"Apps and their advertising partners can use your activity across other apps on this device to personalise ads while still keeping any information about you private and secure.

For example, if you use cooking apps regularly, you may see ads for shopping delivery services or related content in other apps.

You can block an app from sharing your activity data with advertising partners. Android also auto-deletes shared activity data on a regular basis, so an app that you use again might reappear on this list.

While this feature can be turned on, you may not see a list of apps until this feature is fully available and apps start using it."

"It's common for apps and their advertising partners to remember things that you're interested in to personalise your experience. Apps can securely store this information so that it can only be used by their advertising partners to show ads on other apps.

Whether an ad you see is personalised can depend on many factors like this setting, the ad topics setting, your advertising ID settings and whether the app that you’re using personalises ads.

Google requires companies to state publicly that they won’t use this data to re-identify you across apps. Some apps may use your activity to personalise your experience for more than just ads. They may also combine it with other information that they already know about you. Companies are responsible for letting you know how they use your data. ""Learn more about how Google protects your data in our privacy policy"

"Learn more about app-suggested ads"

"Android uses multiple privacy measures, such as aggregation and noising data, to limit the information that apps can share with one another and to help protect your identity.

Your browser may have a similar setting. If ad measurement is on for both Android and your browser, a company may be able to measure the effectiveness of an ad between apps that you use and sites that you visit. Your browsing history is kept private on your device.

""Learn more about ad measurement"

"Android notes topics of interest based on the apps that you've used in the last few weeks.

Later, an app that you use can ask Android for your topics to personalise the ads that you see. Android shares up to three topics while protecting your identity and information about your app usage.

Android auto-deletes topics regularly. As you continue using apps, a topic might reappear on the list. Alternatively, you can block topics that you don't want Android to share with apps.

Whether an ad you see is personalised can depend on many factors, such as this setting, the app-suggested ads setting, your advertising ID settings and whether the app that you're using personalises ads.
